{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613894"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:39:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:39:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16331"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16331"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9022"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113958"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9022"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95973"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7516"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21467"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113958"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA structure in the eye is described as a highly vascularized, muscular diaphragm with a central opening. It contains both sphincter and dilator muscles that control the size of this opening.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures in the eye is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ciliary body","Retina","Choroid","Iris","Tenon\u0027s capsule"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eiris\u003C/strong\u003E is a circular, pigmented muscular diaphragm that controls pupil size. It contains two muscles: the sphincter pupillae (controlled by parasympathetic nerves) which constricts the pupil, and the dilator pupillae (controlled by sympathetic nerves) which dilates the pupil.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eciliary body\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in accommodation and aqueous humor production, not pupil size control. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eretina\u003C/strong\u003E is the light-sensitive neural tissue at the back of the eye. The \u003Cstrong\u003Echoroid\u003C/strong\u003E is a vascular layer that supplies the outer retina. \u003Cstrong\u003ETenon\u0027s capsule\u003C/strong\u003E is a fascial layer surrounding the eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe iris divides the anterior segment of the eye into anterior and posterior chambers and regulates the amount of light entering the eye by adjusting pupil size.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The iris is a pigmented muscular diaphragm that controls pupil size through coordinated action of sphincter and dilator muscles.","The iris divides the anterior segment of the eye into anterior and posterior chambers.","The iris contains two muscles: the sphincter pupillae (parasympathetic) and dilator pupillae (sympathetic)."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95973"}},"question":{"data":{